[3] Kansas: Montgomery County
Date: Mon 20 Jul 2020
Source: The Butler County Times-Gazette [edited]
https://www.butlercountytimesgazette.com/news/20200720/cattle-in-kansas-have-vsv


The USDA has reported that 2 confirmed cattle ranches in Montgomery County, Kansas, have animals with vesicular stomatitis virus. Montgomery County also has 3 new suspect equine premises.

The USDA reports Kansas is among the top VSV-affected states. Other states included in the 2020 outbreak include Arizona [now clear], Missouri, Nebraska, New Mexico, Oklahoma, and Texas.

Kansas has 4 new confirmed positive and 7 new suspect premises.

Butler County has slowed down, with only one new suspect equine premise. Cowley and Sedgwick counties report one new confirmed case, with Cowley also having a suspected case. Miami and Sumner have a new suspected equine case as well.

Animals affected by VSV must be quarantined for 14 days.

[Byline: Alice Mannette]

